{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585882"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:20:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:20:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15028"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15028"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.09,0.03,0.17,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7716"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116018"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7716"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15028"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98014"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5220"},{"type":"tags","id":"5323"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18848"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18851"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116018"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENon-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) can affect kidney function through several mechanisms. This is particularly important in patients with conditions that reduce renal perfusion, such as heart failure, liver cirrhosis, or volume depletion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how NSAIDs affect kidney function?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduced renal blood flow from inhibition of both COX-1 and COX-2","Selective inhibition of COX-2 only","Enhanced prostaglandin synthesis","Selective inhibition of afferent arteriolar tone","Direct stimulation of renin release"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENSAIDs cause \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduced renal blood flow from inhibition of both COX-1 and COX-2\u003C/strong\u003E enzymes, which normally produce vasodilatory prostaglandins. This is particularly important in states of reduced renal perfusion where prostaglandins help maintain blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelective inhibition of COX-2\u003C/strong\u003E only does not accurately describe NSAID action as these drugs affect both COX isoforms. \u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced prostaglandin synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E represents the opposite of what NSAIDs do, as they reduce prostaglandin production. \u003Cstrong\u003ESelective inhibition of afferent arteriolar tone\u003C/strong\u003E oversimplifies the mechanism since NSAIDs affect both afferent and efferent arterioles through reduced prostaglandin synthesis. \u003Cstrong\u003EDirect stimulation of renin release\u003C/strong\u003E contradicts the actual effect of NSAIDs, which actually reduce renin release by inhibiting prostaglandin synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe reduction in prostaglandin synthesis leads to decreased renal blood flow and can precipitate acute kidney injury, particularly in patients with underlying risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) reduce renal blood flow by inhibiting both cyclooxygenase-1 (COX-1) and cyclooxygenase-2 (COX-2) enzymes","Prostaglandins are important vasodilators that help maintain renal blood flow, especially during states of reduced perfusion","NSAID-induced acute kidney injury is most likely in patients with pre-existing reduced renal perfusion"],"references":["LaForge JM, Urso K, Day JM, Bourgeois CW, Ross MM, Ahmadzadeh S, Shekoohi S, Cornett EM, Kaye AM, Kaye AD. Non-steroidal Anti-inflammatory Drugs: Clinical Implications, Renal Impairment Risks, and AKI. Adv Ther. 2023 May;40(5):2082-2096. doi: 10.1007/s12325-023-02481-6. Epub 2023 Mar 22. PMID: 36947330.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98014"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15028"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98014"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T10:36:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T10:36:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7716"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116018"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"ty